Quick check: N/A (no changes).

Analysis summary (7+ sessions):
  The postulate states: β(x,u,v) = fE(τ(x,v).fst) - fE(τ(x,u).fst) for some fE : E'N → ℤ.
  Equivalent to: the Čech cocycle β factors through the E-level ring decomposition.

  New approaches explored this session:
  1. ScottIntCodomain on FP = Σ S (T×T): factors β̃ through FP-level, but
     FP-level ≠ E-level pair. Needs "generation fact" to relate them.
  2. localChoice + section approach: α_C(c,u) = β(x,σ(c),u) on pullback P.
     The difference β(x,u,v) = α_C(c,v) - α_C(c,u) is independent of c,
     but defining fE requires knowing P-level decomposes as (C-part, E-part).
  3. BoolHomFromFiniteFactors: can factor individual ring maps BN-E → B-FP
     through FP-level, but can't show FP-level is DETERMINED by E-level pair.
  4. Direct Čech colimit approach (following tex): Č(S,T,ℤ) = colim Č(S_k,T_k,ℤ),
     each exact. Still requires FP_k = E_k ×_{S_k} E_k (same generation fact).
  5. Stone-Weierstrass for Boolean algebras: B' = subalgebra generated by
     pr₁*(B-E) ∪ pr₂*(B-E) separates points of FP = E ×_S E, so B' = B-FP.
     Correct but requires ~150 lines of new infrastructure.

  ALL approaches converge on the same requirement: the "generation fact" that
  B-FP is generated by pullbacks from B-E via the two projections pr₁*, pr₂*.

  Mathematical proof: B' = subalgebra generated by pr₁*(B-E) ∪ pr₂*(B-E).
  Since FP = E ×_S E, two points (x,u₁,v₁) ≠ (x,u₂,v₂) differ in u or v
  component, so some pullback element distinguishes them. Hence B' separates
  points of FP. By Stone duality, Sp(B') ≃ FP ≃ Sp(B-FP), so B' ≃ B-FP.

  Formalization difficulty: needs either tensor products of Boolean rings,
  Stone-Weierstrass for Boolean algebras, or tracing through the abstract
  StoneSigmaClosed construction. All require ~150-200 lines of new infrastructure.

